# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: wave-function-collapse
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] **CA**) is a discrete model of computation studied in automata theory.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Cellular automata are also called **cellular spaces**, **tessellation automata**, **homogeneous structures**, **cellular structures**, **tessellation structures**, and **iterative arrays**.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Cellular automata have found application in various areas, including physics, theoretical biology, and microstructure modeling.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] A cellular automaton consists of a regular grid of *cells*, each in one of a finite number of *states*, such as *on* and *off* (in contrast to a coupled map lattice).
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] The grid can be in any finite number of dimensions.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] For each cell, a set of cells called its *neighborhood* is defined relative to the specified cell.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] An initial state (time *t* = 0) is selected by assigning a state for each cell.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] A new *generation* is created (advancing *t* by 1), according to some fixed *rule* (generally, a mathematical function) that determines the new state of each cell in terms of the current state of the cell and the states of the cells in its neighborhood.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Typically, the rule for updating the state of cells is the same for each cell and does not change over time, and is applied to the whole grid simultaneously, though exceptions are known, such as the stochastic cellular automaton and asynchronous cellular automaton.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] The concept was originally conceived in the 1940s by Stanislaw Ulam and John von Neumann while they were contemporaries at Los Alamos National Laboratory.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] While studied by some throughout the 1950s and 1960s, it was not until the 1970s and Conway's Game of Life, a two-dimensional cellular automaton, that interest in the subject expanded beyond academia.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] In the 1980s, Stephen Wolfram engaged in a systematic study of one-dimensional cellular automata, or what he calls elementary cellular automata; his research assistant Matthew Cook showed that one of these rules is Turing-complete.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] The primary classifications of cellular automata, as outlined by Wolfram, are numbered one to four.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] This last class is thought to be computationally universal, or capable of simulating a Turing machine.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Special types of cellular automata are *reversible*, where only a single configuration leads directly to a subsequent one, and *totalistic*, in which the future value of individual cells only depends on the total value of a group of neighboring cells.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Cellular automata can simulate a variety of real-world systems, including biological and chemical ones.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] The range-2 "cross neighborhood" includes the pink cells as well.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] One way to simulate a two-dimensional cellular automaton is with an infinite sheet of graph paper along with a set of rules for the cells to follow.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Each square is called a "cell" and each cell has two possible states, black or white.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] The *neighborhood* of a cell is the nearby, usually adjacent, cells.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] The two most common types of neighborhoods are the *von Neumann neighborhood* and the *Moore neighborhood*.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] The former, named after the founding cellular automaton theorist, consists of the four orthogonally adjacent cells.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] The latter includes the von Neumann neighborhood as well as the four diagonally adjacent cells.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] For such a cell and its Moore neighborhood, there are 512 (= 29) possible patterns.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] For each of the 512 possible patterns, the rule table would state whether the center cell will be black or white on the next time interval.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Conway's Game of Life is a popular version of this model.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Another common neighborhood type is the *extended von Neumann neighborhood*, which includes the two closest cells in each orthogonal direction, for a total of eight.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] The general equation for the total number of automata possible is *k**k**s*, where *k* is the number of possible states for a cell, and *s* is the number of neighboring cells (including the cell to be calculated itself) used to determine the cell's next state.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Thus, in the two-dimensional system with a Moore neighborhood, the total number of automata possible would be 229, or 1.34×10154.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] It is usually assumed that every cell in the universe starts in the same state, except for a finite number of cells in other states; the assignment of state values is called a *configuration*.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] More generally, it is sometimes assumed that the universe starts out covered with a periodic pattern, and only a finite number of cells violate that pattern.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] The latter assumption is common in one-dimensional cellular automata.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Cellular automata are often simulated on a finite grid rather than an infinite one.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] In two dimensions, the universe would be a rectangle instead of an infinite plane.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] The obvious problem with finite grids is how to handle the cells on the edges.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] How they are handled will affect the values of all the cells in the grid.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] One possible method is to allow the values in those cells to remain constant.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Another method is to define neighborhoods differently for these cells.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] One could say that they have fewer neighbors, but then one would also have to define new rules for the cells located on the edges.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] These cells are usually handled with periodic boundary conditions resulting in a *toroidal* arrangement: when one goes off the top, one comes in at the corresponding position on the bottom, and when one goes off the left, one comes in on the right.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Universes of other dimensions are handled similarly.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] This solves boundary problems with neighborhoods, but another advantage is that it is easily programmable using modular arithmetic functions.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] For example, in a 1-dimensional cellular automaton like the examples below, the neighborhood of a cell *xit* is {*x**i*−1*t*−1, *x**i**t*−1, *x**i*+1*t*−1}, where *t* is the time step (vertical), and *i* is the index (horizontal) in one generation.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Stanisław Ulam, while working at the Los Alamos National Laboratory in the 1940s, studied the growth of crystals, using a simple lattice network as his model.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] At the same time, John von Neumann — Ulam's colleague at Los Alamos — was working on the problem of self-replicating systems.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Von Neumann's initial design was founded upon the notion of one robot building another robot.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] This design is known as the kinematic model.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] As he developed this design, von Neumann came to realize the great difficulty of building a self-replicating robot, and of the great cost in providing the robot with a "sea of parts" from which to build its replicant.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Neumann wrote a paper entitled "The general and logical theory of automata" for the Hixon Symposium in 1948.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Ulam was the one who suggested using a *discrete* system for creating a reductionist model of self-replication.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Nils Aall Barricelli performed many of the earliest explorations of these models of artificial life.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Ulam and von Neumann created a method for calculating liquid motion in the late 1950s.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] The driving concept of the method was to consider a liquid as a group of discrete units and calculate the motion of each based on its neighbors' behaviors.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Thus was born the first system of cellular automata.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Like Ulam's lattice network, von Neumann's cellular automata are two-dimensional, with his self-replicator implemented algorithmically.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] The result was a universal copier and constructor working within a cellular automaton with a small neighborhood (only those cells that touch are neighbors; for von Neumann's cellular automata, only orthogonal cells), and with 29 states per cell.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Von Neumann gave an existence proof that a particular pattern would make endless copies of itself within the given cellular universe by designing a 200,000 cell configuration that could do so.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] This design is known as the tessellation model, and is called a von Neumann universal constructor.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Also in the 1940s, Norbert Wiener and Arturo Rosenblueth developed a model of excitable media with some of the characteristics of a cellular automaton.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Their specific motivation was the mathematical description of impulse conduction in cardiac systems.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] However their model is not a cellular automaton because the medium in which signals propagate is continuous, and wave fronts are curves.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] A true cellular automaton model of excitable media was developed and studied by J.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Hastings in 1978; see Greenberg-Hastings cellular automaton.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] The original work of Wiener and Rosenblueth contains many insights and continues to be cited in modern research publications on cardiac arrhythmia and excitable systems.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] In the 1960s, cellular automata were studied as a particular type of dynamical system and the connection with the mathematical field of symbolic dynamics was established for the first time.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Hedlund compiled many results following this point of view in what is still considered as a seminal paper for the mathematical study of cellular automata.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] The most fundamental result is the characterization in the Curtis–Hedlund–Lyndon theorem of the set of global rules of cellular automata as the set of continuous endomorphisms of shift spaces.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Also in 1969 computer scientist Alvy Ray Smith completed a Stanford PhD dissertation on Cellular Automata Theory, the first mathematical treatment of CA as a general class of computers.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Many papers came from this dissertation: He showed the equivalence of neighborhoods of various shapes, how to reduce a Moore to a von Neumann neighborhood or how to reduce any neighborhood to a von Neumann neighborhood.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] He proved that two-dimensional CA are computation universal, introduced 1-dimensional CA, and showed that they too are computation universal, even with simple neighborhoods.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] He showed how to subsume the complex von Neumann proof of construction universality (and hence self-reproducing machines) into a consequence of computation universality in a 1-dimensional CA.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Intended as the introduction to the German edition of von Neumann's book on CA, he wrote a survey of the field with dozens of references to papers, by many authors in many countries over a decade or so of work, often overlooked by modern CA researchers.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] In the 1970s a two-state, two-dimensional cellular automaton named Game of Life became widely known, particularly among the early computing community.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Any live cell with two or three live neighbours lives on to the next generation.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Any live cell with more than three live neighbours dies, as if by overpopulation.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Any dead cell with exactly three live neighbours becomes a live cell, as if by reproduction.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Despite its simplicity, the system achieves an impressive diversity of behavior, fluctuating between apparent randomness and order.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] One of the most apparent features of the Game of Life is the frequent occurrence of *gliders*, arrangements of cells that essentially move themselves across the grid.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] It is possible to arrange the automaton so that the gliders interact to perform computations, and after much effort it has been shown that the Game of Life can emulate a universal Turing machine.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] It was viewed as a largely recreational topic, and little follow-up work was done outside of investigating the particularities of the Game of Life and a few related rules in the early 1970s.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Stephen Wolfram independently began working on cellular automata in mid-1981 after considering how complex patterns seemed formed in nature in violation of the second law of thermodynamics.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] His investigations were initially spurred by a desire to model systems such as the neural networks found in brains.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] He published his first paper in *Reviews of Modern Physics* investigating *elementary cellular automata* (Rule 30 in particular) in June 1983.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] The unexpected complexity of the behavior of these simple rules led Wolfram to suspect that complexity in nature may be due to similar mechanisms.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] His investigations, however, led him to realize that cellular automata were poor at modelling neural networks.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Additionally, during this period Wolfram formulated the concepts of intrinsic randomness and computational irreducibility, and suggested that Rule 110 may be universal—a fact proved later by Wolfram's research assistant Matthew Cook in the 1990s.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Wolfram, in *A New Kind of Science* and several papers dating from the mid-1980s, defined four classes into which cellular automata and several other simple computational models can be divided depending on their behavior.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] While earlier studies in cellular automata tended to try to identify types of patterns for specific rules, Wolfram's classification was the first attempt to classify the rules themselves.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] These definitions are qualitative in nature and there is some room for interpretation.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] According to Wolfram, "...with almost any general classification scheme there are inevitably cases which get assigned to one class by one definition and another class by another definition.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] There have been several attempts to classify cellular automata in formally rigorous classes, inspired by Wolfram's classification.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] For instance, Culik and Yu proposed three well-defined classes (and a fourth one for the automata not matching any of these), which are sometimes called Culik–Yu classes; membership in these proved undecidable.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Wolfram's class 2 can be partitioned into two subgroups of stable (fixed-point) and oscillating (periodic) rules.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] A cellular automaton is *reversible* if, for every current configuration of the cellular automaton, there is exactly one past configuration (preimage).
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] If one thinks of a cellular automaton as a function mapping configurations to configurations, reversibility implies that this function is bijective.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] If a cellular automaton is reversible, its time-reversed behavior can also be described as a cellular automaton; this fact is a consequence of the Curtis–Hedlund–Lyndon theorem, a topological characterization of cellular automata.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] For cellular automata in which not every configuration has a preimage, the configurations without preimages are called *Garden of Eden* patterns.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] For one-dimensional cellular automata there are known algorithms for deciding whether a rule is reversible or irreversible.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] However, for cellular automata of two or more dimensions reversibility is undecidable; that is, there is no algorithm that takes as input an automaton rule and is guaranteed to determine correctly whether the automaton is reversible.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] The proof by Jarkko Kari is related to the tiling problem by Wang tiles.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] When a 2D automata is not reversible, often the proof can be trivial as distinct patterns that map to the same state can be quite common.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Reversible cellular automata are often used to simulate such physical phenomena as gas and fluid dynamics, since they obey the laws of thermodynamics.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Such cellular automata have rules specially constructed to be reversible.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Such systems have been studied by Tommaso Toffoli, Norman Margolus and others.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Several techniques can be used to explicitly construct reversible cellular automata with known inverses.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Two common ones are the second-order cellular automaton and the block cellular automaton, both of which involve modifying the definition of a cellular automaton in some way.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Although such automata do not strictly satisfy the definition given above, it can be shown that they can be emulated by conventional cellular automata with sufficiently large neighborhoods and numbers of states, and can therefore be considered a subset of conventional cellular automata.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Conversely, it has been shown that every reversible cellular automaton can be emulated by a block cellular automaton.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] A special class of cellular automata are *totalistic* cellular automata.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] The state of each cell in a totalistic cellular automaton is represented by a number (usually an integer value drawn from a finite set), and the value of a cell at time *t* depends only on the *sum* of the values of the cells in its neighborhood (possibly including the cell itself) at time *t* − 1.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] If the state of the cell at time *t* depends on both its own state and the total of its neighbors at time *t* − 1 then the cellular automaton is properly called *outer totalistic*.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Conway's Game of Life is outer totalistic (but not totalistic), with cell values 0 and 1.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Outer totalistic cellular automata with the same Moore neighborhood structure as Life are sometimes called life-like cellular automata.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] More generally, an *isotropic* ruleset is one that is not necessarily outer totalistic, but still has all the reflection symmetries.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] In the case of a cellular automata on a square grid, the group of symmetries is D8.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] There are many possible generalizations of the cellular automaton concept.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] One way is by using something other than a rectangular (cubic, *etc.*) grid.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] For example, if a plane is tiled with regular hexagons, those hexagons could be used as cells.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] In many cases the resulting cellular automata are equivalent to those with rectangular grids with specially designed neighborhoods and rules.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Another variation would be to make the grid itself irregular, such as with Penrose tiles.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Also, rules can be probabilistic rather than deterministic.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Such cellular automata are called probabilistic cellular automata.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] A probabilistic rule gives, for each pattern at time *t*, the probabilities that the central cell will transition to each possible state at time *t* + 1.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] The neighborhood or rules could change over time or space.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] For example, initially the new state of a cell could be determined by the horizontally adjacent cells, but for the next generation the vertical cells would be used.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] In cellular automata, the new state of a cell is not affected by the new state of other cells.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] This could be changed so that, for instance, a 2 by 2 block of cells can be determined by itself and the cells adjacent to itself.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] These are like totalistic cellular automata, but instead of the rule and states being discrete (*e.g.* a table, using states {0,1,2}), continuous functions are used, and the states become continuous (usually values in [0,1]).
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] The state of a location is a finite number of real numbers.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Certain cellular automata can yield diffusion in liquid patterns in this way.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Continuous spatial automata have a continuum of locations.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Time is also continuous, and the state evolves according to differential equations.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] One important example is reaction–diffusion textures, differential equations proposed by Alan Turing to explain how chemical reactions could create the stripes on zebras and spots on leopards.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] When these are approximated by cellular automata, they often yield similar patterns.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] MacLennan considers continuous spatial automata as a model of computation.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] There are known examples of continuous spatial automata, which exhibit propagating phenomena analogous to gliders in the Game of Life.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] The simplest nontrivial cellular automaton would be one-dimensional, with two possible states per cell, and a cell's neighbors defined as the adjacent cells on either side of it.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] A cell and its two neighbors form a neighborhood of 3 cells, so there are 23 = 8 possible patterns for a neighborhood.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] A rule consists of deciding, for each pattern, whether the cell will be a 1 or a 0 in the next generation.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] These 256 cellular automata are generally referred to by their Wolfram code, a standard naming convention invented by Wolfram that gives each rule a number from 0 to 255.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] A number of papers have analyzed and compared the distinct cases among the 256 cellular automata (many are trivially isomorphic).
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] The rule 30, rule 90, rule 110, and rule 184 cellular automata are particularly interesting.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] The images below show the history of rules 30 and 110 when the starting configuration consists of a 1 (at the top of each image) surrounded by 0s.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Each row of pixels represents a generation in the history of the automaton, with *t*=0 being the top row.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Each pixel is colored white for 0 and black for 1.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Rule 30 exhibits *class 3* behavior, meaning even simple input patterns such as that shown lead to chaotic, seemingly random histories.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Rule 110, like the Game of Life, exhibits what Wolfram calls *class 4* behavior, which is neither completely random nor completely repetitive.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Localized structures appear and interact in various complicated-looking ways.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] In the course of the development of *A New Kind of Science*, as a research assistant to Wolfram in 1994, Matthew Cook proved that some of these structures were rich enough to support universality.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] This result is interesting because rule 110 is an extremely simple one-dimensional system, and difficult to engineer to perform specific behavior.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] This result therefore provides significant support for Wolfram's view that class 4 systems are inherently likely to be universal.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Cook presented his proof at a Santa Fe Institute conference on Cellular Automata in 1998, but Wolfram blocked the proof from being included in the conference proceedings, as Wolfram did not want the proof announced before the publication of *A New Kind of Science*.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] In 2004, Cook's proof was finally published in Wolfram's journal *Complex Systems* (Vol.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] 1), over ten years after Cook came up with it.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Rule 110 has been the basis for some of the smallest universal Turing machines.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] An elementary cellular automaton rule is specified by 8 bits, and all elementary cellular automaton rules can be considered to sit on the vertices of the 8-dimensional unit hypercube.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] This unit hypercube is the cellular automaton rule space.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] For next-nearest-neighbor cellular automata, a rule is specified by 25 = 32 bits, and the cellular automaton rule space is a 32-dimensional unit hypercube.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] A distance between two rules can be defined by the number of steps required to move from one vertex, which represents the first rule, and another vertex, representing another rule, along the edge of the hypercube.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] This rule-to-rule distance is also called the Hamming distance.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Cellular automaton rule space allows us to ask the question concerning whether rules with similar dynamical behavior are "close" to each other.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Graphically drawing a high dimensional hypercube on the 2-dimensional plane remains a difficult task, and one crude locator of a rule in the hypercube is the number of bit-1 in the 8-bit string for elementary rules (or 32-bit string for the next-nearest-neighbor rules).
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Drawing the rules in different Wolfram classes in these slices of the rule space show that class 1 rules tend to have lower number of bit-1s, thus located in one region of the space, whereas class 3 rules tend to have higher proportion (50%) of bit-1s.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] For larger cellular automaton rule space, it is shown that class 4 rules are located between the class 1 and class 3 rules.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] This observation is the foundation for the phrase edge of chaos, and is reminiscent of the phase transition in thermodynamics.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Several biological processes or phenomena can be simulated using cellular automata, which is regarded as a specific type of agent-based model in such application contexts.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] In these biological simulations, it is common for the cells of the cellular automaton to be identified with biological cells.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Additionally, biological phenomena which require explicit modeling of the agents' velocities (for example, those involved in collective cell migration) may be modeled by cellular automata with a more complex state space and rules, such as biological lattice-gas cellular automata.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] The Belousov–Zhabotinsky reaction is a spatio-temporal chemical oscillator that can be simulated by means of a cellular automaton.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Belousov) discovered that when a thin, homogenous layer of a mixture of malonic acid, acidified bromate, and a ceric salt were mixed together and left undisturbed, fascinating geometric patterns such as concentric circles and spirals propagate across the medium.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] In the "Computer Recreations" section of the August 1988 issue of *Scientific American*, A.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Dewdney discussed a cellular automaton developed by Martin Gerhardt and Heike Schuster of the University of Bielefeld (Germany).
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] This automaton produces wave patterns that resemble those in the Belousov-Zhabotinsky reaction.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Probabilistic cellular automata are used in statistical and condensed matter physics to study phenomena like fluid dynamics and phase transitions.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] The Ising model is a prototypical example, in which each cell can be in either of two states called "up" and "down", making an idealized representation of a magnet.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] By adjusting the parameters of the model, the proportion of cells being in the same state can be varied, in ways that help explicate how ferromagnets become demagnetized when heated.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Moreover, results from studying the demagnetization phase transition can be transferred to other phase transitions, like the evaporation of a liquid into a gas; this convenient cross-applicability is known as universality.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] The phase transition in the two-dimensional Ising model and other systems in its universality class has been of particular interest, as it requires conformal field theory to understand in depth.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Other cellular automata that have been of significance in physics include lattice gas automata, which simulate fluid flows.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] In a series of works the so-called *vicinal Cellular Automaton* (vicCA) was proposed and further developed to model the possibly unstable growth and sublimation of vicinal crystal surfaces in 1+1D.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Besides the attachment/detachment events being encoded in the rules of the CA, the adatoms on top of the vicinal form a thin layer, and their thermal motion is modeled by a Monte Carlo module.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] A decisive step further was the transition of the model to 2+1D, where a number of different structures were obtained, referred to by the authors as "vicinal creatures"—step bunches, step meanders, nano-pillars, nanowires, etc.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] The vicCA model was extensively used by Alexey Redkov to develop a Machine Learning algorithm on top of it, significantly speeding up calculations by a factor of 105 while enabling systematic classification of the observed phenomena.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Cellular automaton processors are physical implementations of CA concepts, which can process information computationally.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Processing elements are arranged in a regular grid of identical cells.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] The grid is usually a square tiling, or tessellation, of two or three dimensions; other tilings are possible, but not yet used.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Cell states are determined only by interactions with adjacent neighbor cells.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] No means exists to communicate directly with cells farther away.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] One such cellular automaton processor array configuration is the systolic array.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Cell interaction can be via electric charge, magnetism, vibration (phonons at quantum scales), or any other physically useful means.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] This can be done in several ways so that no wires are needed between any elements.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] This is very unlike processors used in most computers today (von Neumann designs) which are divided into sections with elements that can communicate with distant elements over wires.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Rule 30 was originally suggested as a possible block cipher for use in cryptography.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Two-dimensional cellular automata can be used for constructing a pseudorandom number generator.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Cellular automata have been proposed for public-key cryptography.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] The one-way function is the evolution of a finite CA whose inverse is believed to be hard to find.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Given the rule, anyone can easily calculate future states, but it appears to be very difficult to calculate previous states.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Cellular automata have also been applied to design error correction codes.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Cellular automata have been used in generative music and evolutionary music composition and procedural terrain generation in video games.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Certain types of cellular automata can be used to generate mazes.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Two well-known such cellular automata, Maze and Mazectric, have rulestrings B3/S12345 and B3/S1234.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] In the former, this means that cells survive from one generation to the next if they have at least one and at most five neighbours.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] In the latter, this means that cells survive if they have one to four neighbours.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] If a cell has exactly three neighbours, it is born.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] It is similar to Conway's Game of Life in that patterns that do not have a living cell adjacent to 1, 4, or 5 other living cells in any generation will behave identically to it.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] However, for large patterns, it behaves very differently from Life.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] For a random starting pattern, these maze-generating cellular automata will evolve into complex mazes with well-defined walls outlining corridors.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Mazectric, which has the rule B3/S1234 has a tendency to generate longer and straighter corridors compared with Maze, with the rule B3/S12345.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Since these cellular automaton rules are deterministic, each maze generated is uniquely determined by its random starting pattern.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] This is a significant drawback since the mazes tend to be relatively predictable.
[src:wave-function-collapse/cellular-automaton] Like some of the graph-theory based methods described above, these cellular automata typically generate mazes from a single starting pattern; hence it will usually be relatively easy to find the way to the starting cell, but harder to find the way anywhere else.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] In constraint satisfaction, **local consistency** conditions are properties of constraint satisfaction problems related to the consistency of subsets of variables or constraints.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] They can be used to reduce the search space and make the problem easier to solve.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Various kinds of local consistency conditions are leveraged, including **node consistency**, **arc consistency**, and **path consistency**.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Every local consistency condition can be enforced by a transformation that changes the problem without changing its solutions; such a transformation is called **constraint propagation**.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Constraint propagation works by reducing domains of variables, strengthening constraints, or creating new constraints.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] This leads to a reduction of the search space, making the problem easier to solve by some algorithms.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Constraint propagation can also be used as an unsatisfiability checker, incomplete in general but complete in some particular cases.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Local consistency conditions can be grouped into various classes.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] The original local consistency conditions require that every consistent partial assignment (of a particular kind) can be consistently extended to another variable.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] **Directional consistency** only requires this condition to be satisfied when the other variable is greater than the ones in the assignment, according to a given order.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] **Relational consistency** includes extensions to more than one variable, but this extension is only required to satisfy a given constraint or set of constraints.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] In this article, a constraint satisfaction problem is defined as a set of variables, a set of domains, and a set of constraints.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Variables and domains are associated: the domain of a variable contains all values the variable can take.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] A constraint is composed of a sequence of variables, called its scope, and a set of their evaluations, which are the evaluations *satisfying* the constraint.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] The constraint satisfaction problems referred to in this article are assumed to be in a special form.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] A problem is in *normalized form*, respectively *regular form*, if every sequence of variables is the scope of at most one constraint or exactly one constraint.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] The assumption of regularity done only for binary constraints leads to the *standardized form*.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] These conditions can always be enforced by combining all constraints over a sequence of variables into a single one and/or adding a constraint that is satisfied by all values of a sequence of variables.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] In the figures used in this article, the lack of links between two variables indicate that either no constraint or a constraint satisfied by all values exists between these two variables.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] The "standard" local consistency conditions all require that all consistent partial evaluations can be extended to another variable in such a way that the resulting assignment is consistent.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] A partial evaluation is consistent if it satisfies all constraints whose scope is a subset of the assigned variables.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Node consistency requires that every unary constraint on a variable is satisfied by all values in the domain of the variable, and vice versa.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] This condition can be trivially enforced by reducing the domain of each variable to the values that satisfy all unary constraints on that variable.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] As a result, unary constraints can be neglected and assumed incorporated into the domains.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] For example, given a variable V with a domain of $\left\{1,2,3,4\right\}$ and a constraint $V\leq 3$ , node consistency would restrict the domain to $\left\{1,2,3\right\}$ and the constraint could then be discarded.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] This pre-processing step simplifies later stages.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] A variable of a constraint satisfaction problem is arc consistent with another one if each of its admissible values are consistent with some admissible value of the second variable.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Formally, a variable $x_{i}$ is arc consistent with another variable $x_{j}$ if, for every value a in the domain of $x_{i}$ there exists a value b in the domain of $x_{j}$ such that $(a,b)$ satisfies the binary constraint between $x_{i}$ and $x_{j}$ .
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] A problem is arc consistent if every variable is arc consistent with every other one.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] For example, consider the constraint $x<y$ where the variables range over the domain 1 to 3.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Because x can never be 3, there is no arc from 3 to a value in y so it is safe to remove the value 3 from x 's domain, resulting in $\{1,2\}$ .
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Likewise, y can never be 1, so there is no arc, therefore 1 can be removed from y 's domain, resulting in $\{2,3\}$ .
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Arc consistency can also be defined relative to a specific binary constraint: a binary constraint is arc consistent if every value of one variable has a value of the second variable such that they satisfy the constraint.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] This definition of arc consistency is similar to the above, but is given specific to a constraint.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] This difference is especially relevant for non-normalized problems, where the above definition would consider all constraints between two variables while this one considers only a specific one.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] If a variable is not arc consistent with another one, it can be made so by removing some values from its domain.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] This is the form of constraint propagation that enforces arc consistency: it removes, from the domain of the variable, every value that does not correspond to a value of the other variable.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] This transformation maintains the problem solutions, as the removed values are in no solution anyway.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Constraint propagation can make the whole problem arc consistent by repeating this removal for all pairs of variables.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] This process might have to consider a given pair of variables more than once.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Indeed, removing values from the domain of a variable may cause other variables to become no longer arc consistent with it.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] For example, if $x_{3}$ is arc consistent with $x_{2}$ but the algorithm reduces the domain of $x_{2}$ , arc consistency of $x_{3}$ with $x_{2}$ does not hold any longer, and has to be enforced again.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] A simplistic algorithm would cycle over the pairs of variables, enforcing arc consistency, repeating the cycle until no domains change for a whole cycle.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] The AC-3 algorithm improves over this algorithm by ignoring constraints that have not been modified since they were last analyzed.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] This way, once arc consistency is enforced on a constraint, this constraint is not considered again unless the domain of one of its variables is changed.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Path consistency is a property similar to arc consistency, but considers pairs of variables instead of only one.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] A pair of variables is path-consistent with a third variable if each consistent evaluation of the pair can be extended to the other variable in such a way that all *binary* constraints are satisfied.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] The form of constraint propagation that enforces path consistency works by removing some satisfying assignment from a constraint.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Indeed, path consistency can be enforced by removing from a binary constraint all evaluations that cannot be extended to another variable.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] As for arc consistency, this removal might have to consider a binary constraint more than once.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] As for arc consistency, the resulting problem has the same solutions of the original one, as the removed values are in no solution.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] The form of constraint propagation that enforces path consistency might introduce new constraints.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] When two variables are not related by a binary constraint, they are virtually related by the constraint allowing any pair of values.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] However, some pair of values might be removed by constraint propagation.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] The resulting constraint is no longer satisfied by all pairs of values.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Therefore, it is no longer a virtual, trivial constraint.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] The name "path consistency" derives from the original definition, which involved a pair of variables and a path between them, rather than a pair and a single variable.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] While the two definitions are different for a single pair of variables, they are equivalent when referring to the whole problem.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Arc and path consistency can be generalized to non-binary constraints using tuples of variables instead of a single one or a pair.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] A tuple of $i-1$ variables is i -consistent with another variable if every consistent evaluation of the $i-1$ variables can be extended with a value of the other variable while preserving consistency.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] This definition extends to whole problems in the obvious way.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Strong i -consistency is j -consistency for all $j\leq i$ .
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] The particular case of 2-consistency coincides with arc consistency (all problems are assumed node-consistent in this article).
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] On the other hand, 3-consistency coincides with path consistency only if all constraints are binary, because path consistency does not involve ternary constraints while 3-consistency does.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Another way of generalizing arc consistency is *hyper-arc consistency* or *generalized arc consistency*, which requires extendibility of a single variable in order to satisfy a constraint.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Namely, a variable is hyper-arc consistent with a constraint if every value of the variable can be extended to the other variables of the constraint in such a way the constraint is satisfied.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Constraint propagation (enforcing a form of local consistency) might produce an empty domain or an unsatisfiable constraint.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] In this case, the problem has no solution.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] The converse is not true in general: an inconsistent instance may be arc consistent or path consistent while having no empty domain or unsatisfiable constraint.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Indeed, local consistency is only relative to the consistency of groups of variables.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] For example, arc consistency guarantees that every consistent evaluation of a variable can be consistently extended to another variable.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] However, when a single value of a variable is extended to two other variables, there is no guarantee that these two values are consistent with each other.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] For example, $x_{1}=1$ may be consistent with $x_{2}=1$ and with $x_{3}=1$ , but these two evaluations may not be consistent with each other.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] However, constraint propagation can be used to prove satisfiability in some cases.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] A set of binary constraints that is arc consistent and has no empty domain can be inconsistent only if the network of constraints contains cycles.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Indeed, if the constraints are binary and form an acyclic graph, values can always be propagated across constraints: for every value of a variable, all variables in a constraint with it have a value satisfying that constraint.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] As a result, a solution can be found by iteratively choosing an unassigned variable and recursively propagating across constraints.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] This algorithm never tries to assign a value to a variable that is already assigned, as that would imply the existence of cycles in the network of constraints.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] A similar condition holds for path consistency.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] The special cases in which satisfiability can be established by enforcing arc consistency and path consistency are the following ones.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] 3. enforcing strong n consistency establishes satisfiability of problems containing n variables.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Some definitions or results about relative consistency hold only in special cases.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] When the domains are composed of integers, bound consistency can be defined.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] This form of consistency is based on the consistency of the extreme values of the domains, that is, the minimum and maximum values a variable can take.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] When constraints are algebraic or Boolean, arc consistency is equivalent to adding new constraint or syntactically modifying an old one, and this can be done by suitably composing constraints.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Some kinds of constraints are commonly used.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] For example, the constraint that some variables are all different are often used.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Efficient specialized algorithms for enforcing arc consistency on such constraints exist.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] The constraint enforcing a number of variables to be different is usually written $\mathop {\rm {alldifferent}} (x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n})$ or `alldifferent([X1,...,Xn])`.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] This constraint is equivalent to the non-equality of all pairs of different variables, that is, $x_{i}\not =x_{j}$ for every $i\not =j$ .
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] When the domain of a variable is reduced to a single value, this value can be removed from all other domains by constraint propagation when enforcing arc consistency.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] The use of the specialized constraint allows for exploiting properties that do not hold for individual binary disequalities.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] A first property is that the total number of elements in the domains of all variables must be at least the number of variables.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] More precisely, after arc consistency is enforced, the number of unassigned variables must not exceed the number of values in the union of their domains.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Otherwise, the constraint cannot be satisfied.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] This condition can be checked easily on a constraint in the `alldifferent` form, but does not correspond to arc consistency of the network of disequalities.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] A second property of the single `alldifferent` constraint is that hyper-arc consistency can be efficiently checked using a bipartite matching algorithm.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] In particular, a graph is built with variables and values as the two sets of nodes, and a specialized bipartite graph matching algorithm is run on it to check the existence of such a matching.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] A different kind of constraint that is commonly used is the `cumulative` one.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] It was introduced for problems of scheduling and placement.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] As an example, `cumulative([S1,...,Sm], [D1,...,Dm], [R1,...,Rm], L)` can be used to formalize the condition in which there are `m` activities, each one with starting time `si`, duration `di` and using an amount `ri` of a resource.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] The constraint states that the total available amount of resources is `L`.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Specialized constraint propagation techniques for cumulative constraints exists; different techniques are used depending on which variable domains are already reduced to a single value.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] A third specialized constraint that is used in constraint logic programming is the `element` one.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] In constraint logic programming, lists are allowed as values of variables.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] A constraint `element(I, L, X)` is satisfied if `L` is a list and `X` is the `I`-th element of this list.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Specialized constraint propagation rules for these constraints exist.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] As an example, if `L` and `I` are reduced to a single-value domain, a unique value for `X` can be determined.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] More generally, impossible values of `X` can be inferred from the domain of I and vice versa.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Directional consistency is the variant of arc, path, and i -consistency tailored for being used by an algorithm that assigns values to variables following a given order of variables.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] They are similar to their non-directional counterparts, but only require that a consistent assignment to some variables can be consistently extended to another variable that is greater than them according to the order.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] If an algorithm evaluates variables in the order $x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n}$ , consistency is only useful when it guarantees that values of lower-index variables are all consistent with values of higher-index ones.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] When choosing a value for a variable, values that are inconsistent with all values of an unassigned variable can be neglected.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Indeed, even if these values are all consistent with the current partial evaluation, the algorithm will later fail to find a consistent value for the unassigned variable.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] On the other hand, enforcing consistency with variables that are already evaluated is not necessary: if the algorithm chooses a value that is inconsistent with the current partial evaluation, inconsistency is detected anyway.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Assuming that the order of evaluation of the variables is $x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n}$ , a constraint satisfaction problem is directionally arc consistent if every variable $x_{i}$ is arc consistent with any other variable $x_{j}$ such that $i<j$ .
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Directional path consistency is similar, but two variables $x_{i},x_{j}$ have to be path consistent with $x_{z}$ only if $i,j<z$ .
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Strong directional path consistency means both directional path consistency and directional arc consistency.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Similar definitions can be given for the other forms of consistency.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Constraint propagation enforcing directional arc consistency iterates over variables from the last to the first, enforcing at each step the arc consistency of every variable of lower index with it.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] If the order of the variables is $x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n}$ , this algorithm iterates over variables from $x_{n}$ to $x_{1}$ ; for variable $x_{j}$ , it enforces arc consistency of every variable of index lower than j with $x_{j}$ .
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Directional path consistency and strong directional path consistency can be enforced by algorithms similar to the one for arc consistency.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] They process variables from $x_{n}$ to $x_{1}$ ; for every variable $x_{z}$ two variables $x_{i},x_{j}$ with $i,j<z$ are considered, and path consistency of them with $x_{z}$ is enforced.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] No operation is required if the problem contains no constraint on $x_{i}$ and $x_{z}$ or no constraint between $x_{j}$ and $x_{z}$ .
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] However, even if there is no constraint between $x_{i}$ and $x_{j}$ , a trivial one is assumed.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] If constraint propagation reduces its set of satisfying assignments, it effectively create a new non-trivial constraint.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Constraint propagation enforcing strong directional path consistency is similar, but also enforces arc consistency.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Directional consistency guarantees that partial solutions satisfying a constraint can be consistently extended to another variable of higher index.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] However, it does not guarantee that the extensions to different variables are consistent with each other.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] For example, a partial solution may be consistently extended to variable $x_{i}$ or to variable $x_{j}$ , but yet these two extensions are not consistent with each other.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] There are two cases in which this does not happen, and directional consistency guarantees satisfiability if no domain is empty and no constraint is unsatisfiable.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] The first case is that of a binary constraint problem with an ordering of the variables that makes the ordered graph of constraint having width 1.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Such an ordering exists if and only if the graph of constraints is a tree.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] If this is the case, the width of the graph bounds the maximal number of lower (according to the ordering) nodes a node is joined to.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Directional arc consistency guarantees that every consistent assignment to a variable can be extended to higher nodes, and width 1 guarantees that a node is not joined to more than one lower node.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] As a result, once the lower variable is assigned, its value can be consistently extended to every higher variable it is joined with.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] This extension cannot later lead to inconsistency.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Indeed, no other lower variable is joined to that higher variable, as the graph has width 1.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] The second case in which directional consistency guarantees satisfiability if no domain is empty and no constraint is unsatisfiable is that of binary constraint problems whose graph has induced width 2, using strong directional path consistency.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Indeed, this form of consistency guarantees that every assignment to a variable or a pair of variables can be extended to a higher variable, and width 2 guarantees that this variable is not joined to another pair of lower variables.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] The reason why the induced width is considered instead of the width is that enforcing directional path consistency may add constraints.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Indeed, if two variables are not in the same constraint but are in a constraint with a higher variable, some pairs of their values may violate path consistency.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Removing such pairs creates a new constraint.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] As a result, constraint propagation may produce a problem whose graph has more edges than the original one.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] However, all these edges are necessarily in the induced graph, as they are all between two parents of the same node.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Width 2 guarantees that every consistent partial evaluation can be extended to a solution, but this width is relative to the generated graph.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] As a result, induced width being 2 is required for strong directional path consistency to guarantee the existence of solutions.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Directional i -consistency is the guarantee that every consistent assignment to $i-1$ variables can be consistently extended to another variable that is higher in the order.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Strong directional i -consistency is defined in a similar way, but all groups of *at most* $i-1$ variables are considered.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] If a problem is strongly directionally i -consistent and has width less than i and has no empty domain or unsatisfiable constraint, it has solutions.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Every problem can be made strongly directionally i -consistent, but this operation may increase the width of its corresponding graphs.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] The constraint propagation procedure that enforces directional consistency is similar to that used for directional arc consistency and path consistency.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] The variables are considered in turn, from the last to the first according to the order.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] For variable $x_{k}$ , the algorithm considers every group of $i-1$ variables that have index lower than k and are in a constraint with $x_{k}$ .
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Consistency of these variables with $x_{k}$ is checked and possibly enforced by removing satisfying assignments from the constraint among all these i variables (if any, or creating a new one otherwise).
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] This procedure generates a strongly directional i -consistent instance.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] However, it may also add new constraints to the instance.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] As a result, even if the width of the original problem is i , the width of the resulting instance may be greater.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] If this is the case, directional strong consistency does not imply satisfiability even if no domain is empty and no constraint is unsatisfiable.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] However, constraint propagation only adds constraints to variables that are lower than the one it is currently considering.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] As a result, no constraint over a variable is modified or added once the algorithm has dealt with this variable.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Instead of considering a fixed i , one can modify it to the number of parents of each considered variable (the parents of a variable are the variables of index lower than the variable and that are in a constraint with the variable).
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] This corresponds to considering all parents of a given variables at each step.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] In other words, for each variable $x_{i}$ from the last to the first, all its parents are included in a new constraint that limits their values to the ones that are consistent with $x_{i}$ .
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Since this algorithm can be seen as a modification of the previous one with a value i that is changed to the number of parents of each node, it is called *adaptive consistency*.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] This algorithm enforces strongly directional i -consistency with i equal to the induced width of the problem.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] The resulting instance is satisfiable if and only if no domain or constraint is made empty.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] If this is the case, a solution can be easily found by iteratively setting an unassigned variable to an arbitrary value, and propagating this partial evaluation to other variables.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] This algorithm is not always polynomial-time, as the number of constraints introduced by enforcing strong directional consistency may produce an exponential increase of size.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] The problem is however solvable in polynomial time if the enforcing strong directional consistency does not superpolynomially enlarge the instance.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] As a result, if an instance has induced width bounded by a constant, it can be solved in polynomial time.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Bucket elimination is a satisfiability algorithm.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] It can be defined as a reformulation of adaptive consistency.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Its definitions uses buckets, which are containers for constraint, each variable having an associated bucket.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] A constraint always belongs to the bucket of its highest variable.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] The bucket elimination algorithm proceeds from the highest to the lowest variable in turn.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] At each step, the constraints in the buckets of this variable $x_{i}$ are considered.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] By definition, these constraints only involve variables that are lower than $x_{i}$ .
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] The algorithm modifies the constraint between these lower variables (if any, otherwise it creates a new one).
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] In particular, it enforces their values to be extendible to $x_{i}$ consistently with the constraints in the bucket of $x_{i}$ .
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] This new constraint, if any, is then placed in the appropriate bucket.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Since this constraint only involves variables that are lower than $x_{i}$ , it is added to a bucket of a variable that is lower than $x_{i}$ .
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] This algorithm is equivalent to enforcing adaptive consistency.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Since they both enforce consistency of a variable with all its parents, and since no new constraint is added after a variable is considered, what results is an instance that can be solved without backtracking.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Since the graph of the instance they produce is a subgraph of the induced graph, if the induced width is bounded by a constant the generated instance is of size polynomial in the size of the original instance.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] As a result, if the induced width of an instance is bounded by a constant, solving it can be done in polynomial time by the two algorithms.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] While the previous definitions of consistency are all about consistency of assignments, *relational consistency* involves satisfaction of a given constraint or set of constraints only.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] More precisely, relational consistency implies that every consistent partial assignment can be extended in such a way that a given constraint or set of constraints is satisfied.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Formally, a constraint C on variables X is relational arc consistent with one of its variables x if every consistent assignment to $X\backslash \{x\}$ can be extended to x in such a way C is satisfied.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] The difference between "regular" i consistency and relational arc consistency is that the latter only requires the extended assignment to satisfy a given constraint, while the former requires it to satisfy all relevant constraints.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] This definition can be extended to more than one constraint and more than one variable.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] In particular, relational path consistency is similar to relational arc consistency, but two constraints are used in place of one.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Two constraints are relational path consistent with a variable if every consistent assignment to all their variables but the considered one can be extended in such a way the two constraints are satisfied.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] For more than two constraints, relational m -consistency is defined.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Relational m -consistency involves a set of m constraints and a variable that is in the scope of all these constraints.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] In particular, these m constraints are relational m -consistent with the variable if every consistent assignment to all other variables that are in their scopes can be extended to the variable in such a way these constraints are satisfied.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] A problem is m -relational consistent if every set of m constraints is relational m -consistent with every variable that is in all their scopes.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Strong relational m consistency is defined as above: it is the property of being relational k -consistent for every $k<m$ .
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Relational consistency can also be defined for more variables, instead of one.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] A set of m constraints is relational $(i,m)$ -consistent if every consistent assignment to a subset of i of their variables can be extended to an evaluation to all variables that satisfies all constraints.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] This definition does not exactly extends the above because the variables to which the evaluations are supposed to be extendible are not necessarily in all scopes of the involved constraints.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] If an order of the variables is given, relational consistency can be restricted to the cases when the variables(s) the evaluation should be extendable to follow the other variables in the order.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] This modified condition is called directional relational consistency.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] A constraint satisfaction problem may be relationally consistent, have no empty domain or unsatisfiable constraint, and yet be unsatisfiable.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] There are however some cases in which this is not possible.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] The first case is that of strongly relational m -consistent problem when the domains contain at most m elements.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] In this case, a consistent evaluation of k variables can be always extended to a single other variable.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] If $x_{1}=a_{1},\ldots ,x_{k}=a_{k}$ is such an evaluation and $x_{k+1}$ is the variable, there are only m possible values the variable can take.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] If all such values are inconsistent with the evaluation, there are m (non-necessarily unique) constraints that are violated by the evaluation and one of its possible values.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] As a result, the evaluation cannot be extended to satisfy all these m -or-less constraints, violating the condition of strong relational m -consistency.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] The second case is related to a measure of the constraints, rather than the domains.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] A constraint is m -tight if every evaluation to all its variables but one can be extended to satisfy the constraint either by all possible values of the other variable or by at most m of its values.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Problem having m -tight constraints are satisfiable if and only if they are strongly relationally $m+1$ -consistent.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] The third case is that of binary constraints that can be represented by row-convex matrices.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] A binary constraint can be represented by a bidimensional matrix M , where $M_{ij}$ is 0 or 1 depending on whether the i -th value of the domain of $x_{i}$ and the j -th value of the domain of $x_{j}$ satisfy the constraint.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] A row of this matrix is convex if the 1's it contains are consecutive (formally, if two elements are 1, all elements in between are 1 as well).
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] A matrix is row convex if all its rows are convex.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] The condition that makes strong relational path consistency equivalent to satisfiability is that of constraint satisfaction problems for which there exists an order of the variables that makes all constraint to be represented by row convex matrices.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] This result is based on the fact that a set of convex rows having a common element pairwise also have a globally common element.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Considering an evaluation over k variables, the allowed values for the $k+1$ -th one are given by selecting some rows from some constraints.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] In particular, for every variable among the k ones, the row relative to its value in the matrix representing the constraint relating it with the $k+1$ one represents the allowed values of the latter.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Since these row are convex, and they have a common element pairwise because of path consistency, they also have a shared common element, which represents a value of the last variable that is consistent with the other ones.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] All forms of local consistency can be enforced by constraint propagation, which may reduce the domains of variables and the sets of assignments satisfying a constraint and may introduce new constraints.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Whenever constraint propagation produces an empty domain or an unsatisfiable constraint, the original problem is unsatisfiable.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Therefore, all forms of local consistency can be used as approximations of satisfiability.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] More precisely, they can be used as incomplete unsatisfiability algorithms, as they can prove that a problem is unsatisfiable, but are in general unable to prove that a problem is satisfiable.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Such approximated algorithms can be used by search algorithms (backtracking, backjumping, local search, etc.) as heuristics for telling whether a partial solution can be extended to satisfy all constraints without further analyzing it.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Even if constraint propagation does not produce an empty domain or an unsatisfiable constraint, it may nevertheless reduce the domains or strengthen the constraints.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] If this is the case, the search space of the problem is reduced, thus reducing the amount of search needed to solve the problem.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Local consistency proves satisfiability in some restricted cases (see Complexity of constraint satisfaction#Restrictions).
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] This is the case for some special kind of problems and/or for some kinds of local consistency.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] For example, enforcing arc consistency on binary acyclic problems allows for telling whether the problem is satisfiable.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Enforcing strong directional i -consistency allows telling the satisfiability of problems that have induced width $i-1$ according to the same order.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-propagation] Adaptive directional consistency allows telling the satisfiability of an arbitrary problem.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] These are often provided with tutorials of CP, ASP, Boolean SAT and SMT solvers.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] In the general case, constraint problems can be much harder, and may not be expressible in some of these simpler systems.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] "Real life" examples include automated planning, lexical disambiguation, musicology, product configuration and resource allocation.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] The existence of a solution to a CSP can be viewed as a decision problem.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] This can be decided by finding a solution, or failing to find a solution after exhaustive search (stochastic algorithms typically never reach an exhaustive conclusion, while directed searches often do, on sufficiently small problems).
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] In some cases the CSP might be known to have solutions beforehand, through some other mathematical inference process.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Each variable $X_{i}$ can take on the values in the nonempty domain $D_{i}$ .
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] An *evaluation* of the variables is a function from a subset of variables to a particular set of values in the corresponding subset of domains.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] An evaluation v satisfies a constraint $\langle t_{j},R_{j}\rangle$ if the values assigned to the variables $t_{j}$ satisfy the relation $R_{j}$ .
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] An evaluation is *consistent* if it does not violate any of the constraints.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] An evaluation is *complete* if it includes all variables.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] An evaluation is a *solution* if it is consistent and complete; such an evaluation is said to *solve* the constraint satisfaction problem.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Constraint satisfaction problems on finite domains are typically solved using a form of search.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] The most used techniques are variants of backtracking, constraint propagation, and local search.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] These techniques are also often combined, as in the VLNS method, and current research involves other technologies such as linear programming.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] It maintains a partial assignment of the variables.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Initially, all variables are unassigned.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] At each step, a variable is chosen, and all possible values are assigned to it in turn.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] For each value, the consistency of the partial assignment with the constraints is checked; in case of consistency, a recursive call is performed.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] When all values have been tried, the algorithm backtracks.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] In this basic backtracking algorithm, consistency is defined as the satisfaction of all constraints whose variables are all assigned.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Backmarking improves the efficiency of checking consistency.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Backjumping allows saving part of the search by backtracking "more than one variable" in some cases.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Constraint learning infers and saves new constraints that can be later used to avoid part of the search.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Look-ahead is also often used in backtracking to attempt to foresee the effects of choosing a variable or a value, thus sometimes determining in advance when a subproblem is satisfiable or unsatisfiable.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Constraint propagation techniques are methods used to modify a constraint satisfaction problem.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] More precisely, they are methods that enforce a form of local consistency, which are conditions related to the consistency of a group of variables and/or constraints.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Constraint propagation has various uses.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] First, it turns a problem into one that is equivalent but is usually simpler to solve.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Second, it may prove satisfiability or unsatisfiability of problems.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] This is not guaranteed to happen in general; however, it always happens for some forms of constraint propagation and/or for certain kinds of problems.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] The most known and used forms of local consistency are arc consistency, hyper-arc consistency, and path consistency.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] The most popular constraint propagation method is the AC-3 algorithm, which enforces arc consistency.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Local search methods are incomplete satisfiability algorithms.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] They may find a solution of a problem, but they may fail even if the problem is satisfiable.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] They work by iteratively improving a complete assignment over the variables.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] At each step, a small number of variables are changed in value, with the overall aim of increasing the number of constraints satisfied by this assignment.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] The min-conflicts algorithm is a local search algorithm specific for CSPs and is based on that principle.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] In practice, local search appears to work well when these changes are also affected by random choices.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] An integration of search with local search has been developed, leading to hybrid algorithms.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] CSPs are also studied in computational complexity theory, finite model theory and universal algebra.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] It turned out that questions about the complexity of CSPs translate into important universal-algebraic questions about underlying algebras.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] This approach is known as the *algebraic approach* to CSPs.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Since every computational decision problem is polynomial-time equivalent to a CSP with an infinite template, general CSPs can have arbitrary complexity.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] In particular, there are also CSPs within the class of NP-intermediate problems, whose existence was demonstrated by Ladner, under the assumption that P ≠ NP.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] However, a large class of CSPs arising from natural applications satisfy a complexity dichotomy, meaning that every CSP within that class is either in P or NP-complete.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] These CSPs thus provide one of the largest known subsets of NP which avoids NP-intermediate problems.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] A complexity dichotomy was first proven by Schaefer for Boolean CSPs, i.e.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] CSPs over a 2-element domain and where all the available relations are Boolean operators.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] This result has been generalized for various classes of CSPs, most notably for all CSPs over finite domains.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] This *finite-domain dichotomy conjecture* was first formulated by Tomás Feder and Moshe Vardi, and finally proven independently by Andrei Bulatov and Dmitriy Zhuk in 2017.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Most classes of CSPs that are known to be tractable are those where the hypergraph of constraints has bounded treewidth, or where the constraints have arbitrary form but there exist equationally non-trivial polymorphisms of the set of constraint relations.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] An *infinite-domain dichotomy conjecture* has been formulated for all CSPs of reducts of finitely bounded homogenous structures, stating that the CSP of such a structure is in P if and only if its polymorphism clone is equationally non-trivial, and NP-hard otherwise.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] The complexity of such infinite-domain CSPs as well as of other generalisations (Valued CSPs, Quantified CSPs, Promise CSPs) is still an area of active research.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Every CSP can also be considered as a conjunctive query containment problem.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] A similar situation exists between the functional classes FP and #P.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] By a generalization of Ladner's theorem, there are also problems in neither FP nor #P-complete as long as FP ≠ #P.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] As in the decision case, a problem in the #CSP is defined by a set of relations.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Each problem takes a Boolean formula as input and the task is to compute the number of satisfying assignments.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] This can be further generalized by using larger domain sizes and attaching a weight to each satisfying assignment and computing the sum of these weights.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] It is known that any complex weighted #CSP problem is either in FP or #P-hard.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] The classic model of Constraint Satisfaction Problem defines a model of static, inflexible constraints.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] This rigid model is a shortcoming that makes it difficult to represent problems easily.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Several modifications of the basic CSP definition have been proposed to adapt the model to a wide variety of problems.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Classic CSPs treat constraints as hard, meaning that they are *imperative* (each solution must satisfy all of them) and *inflexible* (in the sense that they must be completely satisfied or else they are completely violated).
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] **Flexible CSP**s relax those assumptions, partially *relaxing* the constraints and allowing the solution to not comply with all of them.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] This is similar to preferences in preference-based planning.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] In DCSPs each constraint variable is thought of as having a separate geographic location.
[src:wave-function-collapse/constraint-satisfaction-problem] Strong constraints are placed on information exchange between variables, requiring the use of fully distributed algorithms to solve the constraint satisfaction problem.
[src:wave-function-collapse/model-synthesis] Some video games known to have utilized variants of the algorithm include *Bad North*, *Townscaper*, and *Caves of Qud*.
[src:wave-function-collapse/model-synthesis] The first example of this type of algorithm was described by Paul Merrell, who termed it 'model synthesis' first in his 2007 i3D paper and also presented at the 2008 SIGGRAPH conference and his 2009 PhD thesis.
[src:wave-function-collapse/model-synthesis] The name 'wave function collapse' later became the popular name for a variant of that algorithm, after an implementation by Maxim Gumin was published in 2016 on a GitHub repository with that name.
[src:wave-function-collapse/model-synthesis] Gumin's implementation significantly popularised this style of algorithm, with it becoming widely adopted and adapted by technical artists and game developers over the following years.
[src:wave-function-collapse/model-synthesis] There were a number of inspirations to Gumin's implementation, including Merrell's PhD dissertation, and convolutional neural network style transfer.
[src:wave-function-collapse/model-synthesis] The popular name for the algorithm, 'wave function collapse', is from an analogy drawn between the algorithm's method and the concept of superposition and observation in quantum mechanics.
[src:wave-function-collapse/model-synthesis] Some innovations present in Gumin's implementation included the usage of overlapping patterns, allowing a single image to be used as an input to the algorithm.
[src:wave-function-collapse/model-synthesis] Some have speculated that the reason Gumin's implementation proved more popular than Merrell's, may have been due to the 'model synthesis' implementation's lower accessibility, its 3D focus, or perhaps the general public's computing constraints at the time.
[src:wave-function-collapse/model-synthesis] One of the differences between Merrell & Gumin's implementation and 'wave function collapse' lies in the decision of which cell to 'collapse' next.
[src:wave-function-collapse/model-synthesis] Merrell's implementation uses a scanline approach, whereas Gumin's always selects as next cell the one with the lowest entropy.
[src:wave-function-collapse/model-synthesis] The WFC or 'model synthesis' algorithm has some variants.
[src:wave-function-collapse/model-synthesis] An array is created with the dimensions of the output desired.
[src:wave-function-collapse/model-synthesis] Once all cells are 'collapsed' into a definite state, return the output.
[src:wave-function-collapse/model-synthesis] If the output is illegal, discard it, and repeat the process until legal.
[src:wave-function-collapse/model-synthesis] Merrell's earlier implementation is substantially the same as Gumin's with some minor differences.
[src:wave-function-collapse/model-synthesis] (1) In Merrell's version, there is no requirement to select the cell with the lowest number of possible output states for collapse.
[src:wave-function-collapse/model-synthesis] Instead, a scanline approach is adopted.
[src:wave-function-collapse/model-synthesis] According to Merrell, this results in a lower failure rate of the model without any negative effect on quality.
[src:wave-function-collapse/model-synthesis] Some commentators have noted however that the scanline approach to 'collapse' tends to result in directional artifacts.
[src:wave-function-collapse/model-synthesis] (2) Merrell's approach performs the algorithm in chunks, rather than all-at-once.
[src:wave-function-collapse/model-synthesis] This approach greatly reduces the failure rate for many large complex models; especially in a 3D space.
[src:wave-function-collapse/model-synthesis] In April 2023 Shaad Alaka and Rafael Bidarra of Delft University proposed 'Hierarchical Semantic wave function collapse'.
[src:wave-function-collapse/model-synthesis] Essentially, the algorithm is modified to work beyond simple, unstructured sets of tiles.
[src:wave-function-collapse/model-synthesis] Prior to their work, all WFC algorithm variants operated on a flat set of tile choices per cell.
[src:wave-function-collapse/model-synthesis] Their generalised approach organizes tile-sets into a hierarchy, consisting of abstract nodes called 'meta-tiles', and terminating nodes called 'leaf tiles'.
[src:wave-function-collapse/model-synthesis] For example, on the first pass, WFC might make a certain tile a meta-tile of 'castle' type; which on a second pass will be collapsed into other tiles based on a rule, e.g. a 'wall' or 'grass' tile.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] In computing, **procedural generation** is a method of creating data algorithmically as opposed to manually, typically through a combination of human-generated content and algorithms coupled with computer-generated randomness and processing power.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] In computer graphics, it is commonly used to create textures and 3D models.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] In video games, it is used to automatically create large amounts of content in a game.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] Depending on the implementation, advantages of procedural generation can include smaller file sizes, larger amounts of content, and randomness for less predictable gameplay.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] The term *procedural* refers to the process that computes a particular function.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] Fractals are geometric patterns which can often be generated procedurally.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] Commonplace procedural content includes textures and meshes.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] Sound is often also procedurally generated, and has applications in both speech synthesis as well as music.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] It has been used to create compositions in various genres of electronic music by artists such as Brian Eno who popularized the term "generative music".
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] Procedural generation was originally created as an instrument for video games, aiding in generating levels, textures and complete worlds with little human contribution.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] Procedurally generated elements have appeared in video games since the 1990s: *The Elder Scrolls II: Daggerfall* takes place in a mostly procedurally generated world, giving a world roughly two thirds the actual size of the British Isles.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] *Soldier of Fortune* from Raven Software uses simple routines to detail enemy models, while its sequel featured a randomly generated level mode.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] Avalanche Studios employed procedural generation to create a large and varied group of detailed tropical islands for *Just Cause*.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] *No Man's Sky*, a game developed by games studio Hello Games, is all based upon procedurally generated elements.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] The modern demoscene uses procedural generation to package a great deal of audiovisual content into relatively small programs.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] New methods and applications are presented annually in conferences such as the IEEE Conference on Computational Intelligence and Games and the AAAI Conference on Artificial Intelligence and Interactive Digital Entertainment.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] Particularly in the application of procedural generation with video games, which are intended to be highly replayable, there are concerns that procedural systems can generate infinite numbers of worlds to explore, but without sufficient human guidance and rules to guide these.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] Using procedural generation in games had origins in tabletop role playing games (RPG).
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] The leading tabletop system, *Advanced Dungeons & Dragons*, provided ways for the "dungeon master" to generate dungeons and terrain using random die rolls, expanded in later editions with complex branching procedural tables.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] Strategic Simulations under license from TSR released the *Dungeon Master's Assistant*, a computer program that generated dungeons based on these published tables.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] *Tunnels & Trolls*, published by Flying Buffalo, was designed primarily around solitary play and used similar procedural generation for its dungeons.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] Other tabletop RPGs borrowed similar concepts in procedural generation for various world elements.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] Many online tools for Dungeon Masters now use procedural generation to varying degrees.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] Prior to graphically oriented video games, roguelike games, a genre directly inspired by *Dungeons & Dragons* adopted for solitary play, heavily utilized procedural generation to randomly produce dungeons, in the same manner that tabletop systems had done.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] Such early games include *Beneath Apple Manor* (1978) and the genre's namesake, *Rogue* (1980).
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] The procedural generation system in roguelikes would create dungeons in ASCII- or regular tile-based systems and define rooms, hallways, monsters, and treasure to challenge the player.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] Roguelikes, and games based on the roguelike concepts, allow the development of complex gameplay without having to spend excessive time in creating a game's world.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] 1978's *Maze Craze* for the Atari VCS used an algorithm to generate a random, top-down maze for each game.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] Some games used pseudorandom number generators.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] These PRNGs were often used with predefined seed values in order to generate very large game worlds that appeared to be premade.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] *The Sentinel* supposedly had 10,000 different levels stored in only 48 and 64 kilobytes.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] An extreme case was *Elite*, which was originally planned to contain a total of 248 (approximately 282 trillion) galaxies with 256 solar systems each.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] However, the publisher was afraid that such a gigantic universe would cause disbelief in players, and eight of these galaxies were chosen for the final version.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] Though modern computer games do not have the same memory and hardware restrictions that earlier games had, the use of procedural generation is frequently employed to create randomized games, maps, levels, characters, or other facets that are unique on each playthrough.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] This also extends to power-ups and other items that populate the game's map, selected by the game through procedural generational rules to assure the game feels fair to the player so they feel they have the agency to win the game.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] Procedural generation is often used in loot systems of quest-driven games, such as action role-playing games and massive multiplayer online role playing games.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] Though quests may feature fixed rewards, other loot, such as weapons and armor, may be generated for the player based on the player-character's level, the quest's level, their performance in the quest, and other random factors.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] This often leads to loot having a rarity quality applied to reflect when the procedural generation system has produced an item with better-than-average attributes.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] For example, the *Borderlands* series is based on its procedural generation system which can create over a million unique guns and other equipment.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] Many open world or survival games procedurally create a game world from a random seed or one provided by the player, so that each playthrough is different.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] These generation systems create numerous pixel- or voxel-based biomes with distribution of resources, objects, and creatures.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] The player frequently has the ability to adjust some of the generation parameters, such as specifying the amount of water coverage in a world.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] Procedural generation is also used in space exploration and trading games.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] *Elite: Dangerous*, through using the 400 billion known stars of the Milky Way Galaxy as its world basis, uses procedural generation to simulate the planets in these solar systems.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] Similarly, *Star Citizen* uses the technology to create seamlessly loaded planets among its hand-crafted universe.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] *Outerra Anteworld* is a video game in development that uses procedural generation and real world data to create a virtual replica of planet Earth in true scale.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] As in video games, procedural generation is often used in film to create visually interesting and accurate spaces rapidly.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] This comes in a wide variety of applications.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] One application is *imperfect factories*, which are used by artists to rapidly generate many similar objects.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] This accounts for the fact that, in real life, no two objects are ever exactly alike.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] For instance, an artist can model a product for a grocery store, and then create an imperfect factory to generate many imperfect copies to populate a whole shelf.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] MASSIVE is a high-end computer animation and artificial intelligence software package used for generating crowd-related visual effects for film and television.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] It was developed to create fighting armies of hundreds of thousands of soldiers for Peter Jackson's *The Lord of the Rings* films automatically.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] Coherent noise can be extremely important to procedural workflow in film.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] Simplex noise is often faster with fewer artifacts, though an older function called Perlin noise may be used as well.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] Coherent noise, in this case, refers to a function that generates smooth pseudo-randomness in *n* dimensions.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] Poyck studied how procedurally generated cityscapes can be used to aid social simulations and to train self-driving cars.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] Procedural generation plays a pivotal part in the progression of digital twins, which are very detailed virtual replicas of real-world objects used for simulation, analysis, and planning.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] Neural networks have recently been employed to refine procedurally generated content.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] Combining classic randomization methods with deep learning provides new ways for generating audio, images, 3D objects, and other content types.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] This is especially useful in game level development; reinforcement learning allows the development of agents that play generated levels, serving as automatic content evaluators.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] Integrating procedural generation with deep learning alters the landscape of digital content creation.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] Zakaria et al. demonstrated that different deep learning methods for procedurally generating Sokoban levels have different strengths and weaknesses.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] Looking ahead, researchers are investigating methods to combine large language models (LLMs) with deep-learning powered procedural generation systems, aiming to enhance their adaptability.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] Zakaria suggests that "LLMs combined with reinforcement learning can create procedural assets that evolve dynamically based on real-time feedback".
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] Zakaria investigated the application of advanced deep learning structures such as bootstrapped LSTM (Long short-term memory) generators and GANs (Generative adversarial networks) to upgrade procedural level design.
[src:wave-function-collapse/procedural-generation] They found that "diversity sampling consistently increases the numbers of generated solutions and signatures", showing that hybrid approaches help overcome problems like repetitive patterns or lack of variation.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] In various interpretations of quantum mechanics, **wave function collapse**, also called **reduction of the state vector**, occurs when a wave function—initially in a superposition of several eigenstates—reduces to a single eigenstate due to interaction with the external world.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] This interaction is called an *observation* and is the essence of a measurement in quantum mechanics, which connects the wave function with classical observables such as position and momentum.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] Collapse is one of the two processes by which quantum systems evolve in time; the other is the continuous evolution governed by the Schrödinger equation.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] In the Copenhagen interpretation, wave function collapse connects quantum to classical models, with a special role for the observer.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] By contrast, objective-collapse proposes an origin in physical processes.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] In the many-worlds interpretation, collapse does not exist; all wave function outcomes occur while quantum decoherence accounts for the appearance of collapse.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] Historically, Werner Heisenberg was the first to use the idea of wave function reduction to explain quantum measurement.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] In quantum mechanics each measurable physical quantity of a quantum system is called an observable which, for example, could be the position r and the momentum p but also energy E , z components of spin ( $s_{z}$ ), and so on.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] The observable acts as a linear function on the states of the system; its eigenvectors correspond to the quantum state (i.e. eigenstate) and the eigenvalues to the possible values of the observable.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] The collection of eigenstates/eigenvalue pairs represent all possible values of the observable.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] The wave function is a specific representation of a quantum state.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] Wave functions can therefore always be expressed as eigenstates of an observable though the converse is not necessarily true.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] where the arrow represents a measurement of the observable corresponding to the $\phi$ basis.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] For any single event, only one eigenvalue is measured, chosen randomly from among the possible values.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] The square modulus $|c_{i}|^{2}$ is the probability that a measurement of the observable yields the eigenstate $|\phi _{i}\rangle$ .
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] As examples, individual counts in a double slit experiment with electrons appear at random locations on the detector; after many counts are summed the distribution shows a wave interference pattern.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] In a Stern-Gerlach experiment with silver atoms, each particle appears in one of two areas unpredictably, but the final conclusion has equal numbers of events in each area.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] This statistical aspect of quantum measurements differs fundamentally from classical mechanics.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] In quantum mechanics the only information we have about a system is its wave function and measurements of its wave function can only give statistical information.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] The two terms "reduction of the state vector" (or "state reduction" for short) and "wave function collapse" are used to describe the same concept.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] A quantum state is a mathematical description of a quantum system; a quantum state vector uses Hilbert space vectors for the description.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] Reduction of the state vector replaces the full state vector with a single eigenstate of the observable.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] The term "wave function" is typically used for a different mathematical representation of the quantum state, one that uses spatial coordinates also called the "position representation".
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] When the wave function representation is used, the "reduction" is called "wave function collapse".
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] The Schrödinger equation describes quantum systems but does not describe their measurement.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] Solutions to the equation include all possible observable values for measurements, but measurements only result in one definite outcome.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] This difference is called the measurement problem of quantum mechanics.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] To predict measurement outcomes from quantum solutions, the orthodox interpretation of quantum theory postulates wave function collapse and uses the Born rule to compute the probable outcomes.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] Despite the widespread quantitative success of these postulates scientists remain dissatisfied and have sought more detailed physical models.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] Rather than suspending the Schrödinger equation during the process of measurement, the measurement apparatus should be included and governed by the laws of quantum mechanics.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] Quantum theory offers no dynamical description of the "collapse" of the wave function.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] Viewed as a statistical theory, no description is expected.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] As Fuchs and Peres put it, "collapse is something that happens in our description of the system, not to the system itself".
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] Various interpretations of quantum mechanics attempt to provide a physical model for collapse.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] Three treatments of collapse can be found among the common interpretations.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] The first group includes hidden-variable theories like de Broglie–Bohm theory; here random outcomes only result from unknown values of hidden variables.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] Results from tests of Bell's theorem shows that these variables would need to be non-local.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] The second group models measurement as quantum entanglement between the quantum state and the measurement apparatus.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] This results in a simulation of classical statistics called quantum decoherence.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] This group includes the many-worlds interpretation and consistent histories models.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] The third group postulates additional, but as yet undetected, physical basis for the randomness; this group includes for example the objective-collapse interpretations.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] While models in all groups have contributed to better understanding of quantum theory, no alternative explanation for individual events has emerged as more useful than collapse followed by statistical prediction with the Born rule.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] The significance ascribed to the wave function varies from interpretation to interpretation and even within an interpretation (such as the Copenhagen interpretation).
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] If the wave function merely encodes an observer's knowledge of the universe, then the wave function collapse corresponds to the receipt of new information.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] This is somewhat analogous to the situation in classical physics, except that the classical "wave function" does not necessarily obey a wave equation.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] If the wave function is physically real, in some sense and to some extent, then the collapse of the wave function is also seen as a real process, to the same extent.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] Quantum decoherence explains why a system interacting with an environment transitions from being a pure state, exhibiting superpositions, to a mixed state, an incoherent combination of classical alternatives.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] Decoherence is thus very important for explaining the classical limit of quantum mechanics, but cannot explain wave function collapse, as all classical alternatives are still present in the mixed state, and wave function collapse selects only one of them.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] The form of decoherence known as environment-induced superselection proposes that when a quantum system interacts with the environment, the superpositions *apparently* reduce to mixtures of classical alternatives.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] The combined wave function of the system and environment continue to obey the Schrödinger equation throughout this *apparent* collapse.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] More importantly, this is not enough to explain *actual* wave function collapse, as decoherence does not reduce it to a single eigenstate.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] Heisenberg did not try to specify exactly what the collapse of the wavefunction meant.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] However, he emphasized that it should not be understood as a physical process.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] Niels Bohr never mentions wave function collapse in his published work, but he repeatedly cautioned that we must give up a "pictorial representation".
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] Despite the differences between Bohr and Heisenberg, their views are often grouped together as the "Copenhagen interpretation", of which wave function collapse is regarded as a key feature.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] The deterministic, unitary, continuous time evolution of an isolated system that obeys the Schrödinger equation.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] In 1957 Hugh Everett III proposed a model of quantum mechanics that dropped von Neumann's first postulate.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] Everett observed that the measurement apparatus was also a quantum system and its quantum interaction with the system under observation should determine the results.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] He proposed that the discontinuous change is instead a splitting of a wave function representing the universe.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] While Everett's approach rekindled interest in foundational quantum mechanics, it left core issues unresolved.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] Two key issues relate to origin of the observed classical results: what causes quantum systems to appear classical and to resolve with the observed probabilities of the Born rule.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] Dieter Zeh sought a detailed quantum decoherence model for the discontinuous change without postulating collapse.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] Zurek in 1980 lead eventually to a large number of papers on many aspects of the concept.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] Decoherence assumes that every quantum system interacts quantum mechanically with its environment and such interaction is not separable from the system, a concept called an "open system".
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] Decoherence has been shown to work very quickly and within a minimal environment, but as yet it has not succeeded in a providing a detailed model replacing the collapse postulate of orthodox quantum mechanics.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] By explicitly dealing with the interaction of object and measuring instrument, von Neumann described a quantum mechanical measurement scheme consistent with wave function collapse.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] However, he did not prove the *necessity* of such a collapse.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] Von Neumann's projection postulate was conceived based on experimental evidence available during the 1930s, in particular Compton scattering.
[src:wave-function-collapse/wave-function-collapse] Later work refined the notion of measurements into the more easily discussed *first kind*, that will give the same value when immediately repeated, and the *second kind* that give different values when repeated.
